YouTube Ad & Theme Story

Introduction

In this visual data story, we explore how YouTube’s recommendation algorithm surfaces advertising content in the first five video suggestions of the homepage. Drawing upon 20 days of observational logging, we examine the distribution of ads, their relationship with content themes, and temporal patterns over time. Our goal is to communicate not only the quantitative patterns but also the narrative behind each visualization.

Data Overview

The dataset consists of 20 observations collected between March 25 and March 31, 2025. Each record captures:

  • Timestamp of the observation
  • Ad count: number of ads or sponsored content in the first five recommendations
  • Content themes: one or more themes (e.g., Technology/Digital, Gaming/eSports)
  • Video format: type of video (Long video, Short video, Live Stream, or Shorts)

This story uses four key visualizations saved as PNG files: plot1.png through plot4.png.

Distribution of Ads

Figure 1.Frequency distribution of the number of advertisements in the first five recommendations. 0 advertisements appeared about 10 times, 1 advertisement appeared about 10 times, 2 advertisements appeared about 8 times, 3 advertisements appeared about 6 times, 4 advertisements appeared about 3 times, and 3 advertisements appeared about 3 times.

Average Ads by Content Theme

Figure 2. Average number of ads per content theme. “cats” has the highest average (around 5 ads), followed by “pet video” (~4 ads), “Gaming/eSports” (~2.2 ads), and “Education/Knowledge” the lowest (under 1 ads).

Total Ads Over Time

Figure 3. Daily total ads in the first five recommendations. Most days range between 3 and 6 total ads, with a significant peak of 47 ads on March 31.

Ad Distribution by Video Format

Figure 4. Distribution of ad counts by video format. Shorts and Live Streams exhibit greater variability and more outliers, while long videos (>10 mins) show a tighter, more consistent ad count distribution.
